# Laravel Query Style Rules

## When to use `Model::query()`

Use **`Model::query()`** only when building a **read** chain that fetches or inspects rows: chains ending in **`get()`**, **`first()`**, **`firstOrFail()`**, **`paginate()`**, **`simplePaginate()`**, **`cursor()`**, **`pluck()`**, **`value()`**, **`exists()`**, **`doesntExist()`**, **`count()`**, etc.

Do **not** start with **`Model::query()`** for **create**, **update**, **delete**, **destroy**, **insert**, **upsert**, or other writes—use the appropriate API without a leading `query()` (e.g. **`Model::create()`**, **`Model::where(...)->update()`**, **`$model->update()`**, **`Model::destroy()`**).

## Model Query (reads)
✔
```php
User::query()
    ->where('status', 1)
    ->get();
```
✖
```php
User::where('status', 1)->get();
```

## Writes (no `query()`)
✔
```php
User::create([
    'name' => $name,
    'email' => $email,
]);

$user->update([
    'name' => $name,
]);

User::where('status', 'inactive')
    ->update(['archived' => true]);

User::destroy($id);
```
✖
```php
User::query()->create([/* ... */]);

User::query()
    ->where('status', 'inactive')
    ->update(['archived' => true]);
```

## Chaining
✔
```php
User::query()
    ->with(['parents'])
    ->withCount(['children'])
    ->where('status', 1)
    ->get();
```
✖
```php
User::query()->where('status', 1)->with('parents')->get();
```

## with() and withCount()
When eager loading relations or relation counts, chain **`with()`** then **`withCount()`** (if needed) **immediately after** `Model::query()`, **before any method that constrains or sorts the main model query**.

**`addSelect` / `select` on the parent:** When **`with()`** or **`withCount()`** is used, chain **`addSelect`** (and parent **`select`**) **immediately after** the last of `with` / `withCount`—**below** them, **before** any parent constraint or sort. If there is no eager loading, `addSelect` / `select` follow `query()` as usual.

**Comes after `with` / `withCount` and after parent `addSelect` / `select` (non-exhaustive):** `where`, `whereKey`, `whereIn`, `whereNull`, `whereHas`, `whereDoesntHave`, `whereExists`, scopes that add `where` / `join` on the parent, `when(...)` / custom `scopeWhen*` that add constraints, `orderBy`, `latest`, `groupBy`, `having`, `limit` / `take`, `skip` / `offset`, `paginate`, etc.

**Closure arguments inside `with([...])` or `withCount([...])`** may use `where` on the **relation subquery** only—that does not violate this rule.

✔
```php
Model::query()
    ->with([
        'relationA',
        'relationB' => fn ($query) => $query->where('active', true),
    ])
    ->withCount([
        'items',
        'items as active_items_count' => fn ($query) => $query->where('status', 'active'),
    ])
    ->where('status', 1)
    ->orderBy('name')
    ->get();
```
✔
```php
Model::query()
    ->with(['relationA'])
    ->withCount(['items'])
    ->addSelect('id', 'name')
    ->where('status', 1)
    ->get();
```
✖
```php
Model::query()
    ->addSelect('id', 'name')
    ->with(['relationA'])
    ->where('status', 1)
    ->get();
```
✖
```php
Model::query()
    ->where('status', 1)
    ->with(['relationA'])
    ->withCount(['items'])
    ->get();
```
✖
```php
// whereKey / when(...) also count as parent constraints — with() must still be first
Model::query()
    ->whereKey($id)
    ->with(['relationA'])
    ->when($condition, fn ($q) => $q->where('published', true))
    ->first();
```
✔
```php
Model::query()
    ->with(['relationA'])
    ->whereKey($id)
    ->when($condition, fn ($q) => $q->where('published', true))
    ->first();
```

## whereHas
✔
```php
User::query()
    ->with(['profile'])
    ->withCount(['posts'])
    ->whereHas('studentNurseries', function ($query) {

        $query->where('nursery_student.status', NurseryStudentStatusEnum::ACTIVE);

    })
    ->get();
```
✖
```php
User::query()
    ->whereHas('studentNurseries', function ($query) {
        $query->where('nursery_student.status', NurseryStudentStatusEnum::ACTIVE);
    })
    ->get();
```

## Final Method
✔
```php
User::query()
    ->where('status', 1)
    ->get();
```
✖
```php
User::query()
    ->where('status', 1)->get();
```

## Rules
- Use **`Model::query()`** for **read** chains (fetch / inspect results). Do **not** use **`Model::query()`** for create, update, delete, destroy, insert, upsert.
- After `query()`, when using eager loading, chain `with()` then `withCount()` (omit either if not needed), then parent **`addSelect` / `select`** if needed, **before every other parent-model constraint**, including `where`, `whereKey`, `whereHas`, `when` / scope helpers that add `where`, and `orderBy`
- Each -> on new line
- No inline chains
- Empty line after { and before }
- Indent closures
- Final method on new line
- Use 4 spaces
